1
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:08,000
Every live event production team knows the feeling.

2
00:00:08,300 --> 00:00:10,300
The keynote runs long.

3
00:00:10,600 --> 00:00:13,225
Or a panel goes fifteen minutes over.

4
00:00:13,525 --> 00:00:17,275
Suddenly your entire afternoon programme is out of sync —

5
00:00:17,575 --> 00:00:20,575
and you're the only person who knows it.

6
00:00:20,875 --> 00:00:24,625
In this episode we're going to look at one of

7
00:00:24,925 --> 00:00:27,550
CueDeck's most useful features: the delay cascade.

8
00:00:27,850 --> 00:00:31,600
It's how you absorb overruns without losing control of your

9
00:00:31,900 --> 00:00:35,275
programme, and it takes about three seconds to use.

10
00:00:35,575 --> 00:00:39,325
Before we hit any buttons, let's understand the two numbers

11
00:00:39,625 --> 00:00:41,625
CueDeck tracks behind the scenes.

12
00:00:41,925 --> 00:00:45,300
Every session in the database has a `planned_start` and

13
00:00:45,600 --> 00:00:50,475
a `planned_end` — those are the times your programme was originally designed around.

14
00:00:50,775 --> 00:00:52,775
They never change.

15
00:00:53,075 --> 00:00:55,325
Think of them as your baseline.

16
00:00:55,625 --> 00:00:59,375
When you apply a delay, CueDeck writes to a separate

17
00:00:59,675 --> 00:01:01,925
pair of fields: `scheduled_start` and `scheduled_end`.

18
00:01:02,225 --> 00:01:04,475
These are the working times —

19
00:01:04,775 --> 00:01:07,775
the live reality of your programme right now.

20
00:01:08,075 --> 00:01:11,825
On top of that, each session carries two delay counters.

21
00:01:12,125 --> 00:01:15,875
`delay_minutes` is the delay applied directly to this specific session

22
00:01:16,175 --> 00:01:18,800
— it's what caused the original ripple.

23
00:01:19,100 --> 00:01:22,475
`cumulative_delay` is the total shift this session has accumulated,

24
00:01:22,775 --> 00:01:26,900
which can be larger if multiple delays have been applied upstream.

25
00:01:27,200 --> 00:01:30,950
You can see the cumulative delay on every affected session

26
00:01:31,250 --> 00:01:33,875
card — that amber tag showing plus-something-minutes.

27
00:01:34,175 --> 00:01:37,925
That number tells you how far behind the original programme

28
00:01:38,225 --> 00:01:40,475
this session is sitting right now.

29
00:01:40,775 --> 00:01:45,275
This session, for example, is running ten minutes behind its planned start.

30
00:01:45,575 --> 00:01:47,825
The director applied a delay upstream,

31
00:01:48,125 --> 00:01:50,750
and it cascaded down to here automatically.

32
00:01:51,050 --> 00:01:53,675
Let me show you how that works.

33
00:01:53,975 --> 00:01:57,350
In the director view, whenever a session is READY,

34
00:01:57,650 --> 00:02:01,400
CALLING, or LIVE, you'll see a row of amber buttons

35
00:02:01,700 --> 00:02:04,325
labeled +MIN — five, ten, and fifteen.

36
00:02:04,625 --> 00:02:06,625
These are your delay controls.

37
00:02:06,925 --> 00:02:10,675
Let's say the current session was scheduled to end at

38
00:02:10,975 --> 00:02:14,725
two-fifteen, but it's two-twenty and the speaker is still going.

39
00:02:15,025 --> 00:02:17,025
I'll hit plus-five.

40
00:02:17,325 --> 00:02:19,325
Watch the session list.

41
00:02:19,625 --> 00:02:21,875
Every session below this one that

42
00:02:22,175 --> 00:02:25,925
is in a PLANNED state just shifted forward five minutes.

43
00:02:26,225 --> 00:02:28,475
Their `scheduled_start` and `scheduled_end` both moved.

44
00:02:28,775 --> 00:02:32,150
The amber plus-five tag appeared on each of them.

45
00:02:32,450 --> 00:02:35,825
And up at the top of the session list,

46
00:02:36,125 --> 00:02:39,875
the delay strip appeared — it tells us the programme

47
00:02:40,175 --> 00:02:43,550
is now running plus-five minutes, with three sessions affected.

48
00:02:43,850 --> 00:02:48,350
The director console doesn't reload, it doesn't ask for a confirmation dialog.

49
00:02:48,650 --> 00:02:51,650
The cascade happens client-side first for instant feedback,

50
00:02:51,950 --> 00:02:55,700
and then writes to the database in the background for

51
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:58,000
all other connected devices.

52
00:02:58,300 --> 00:03:01,675
But here's the scenario most multi-day conferences run into:

53
00:03:01,975 --> 00:03:04,600
you have fixed-time slots that cannot move.

54
00:03:04,900 --> 00:03:07,150
The lunch break at one o'clock.

55
00:03:07,450 --> 00:03:09,450
The opening ceremony.

56
00:03:09,750 --> 00:03:11,750
The gala dinner at seven.

57
00:03:12,050 --> 00:03:15,800
Those sessions need to hold their ground no matter what

58
00:03:16,100 --> 00:03:18,100
happens in the morning.

59
00:03:18,400 --> 00:03:20,650
That's what anchor sessions are for.

60
00:03:20,950 --> 00:03:24,700
When you tick the Anchor checkbox on a session in

61
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:27,250
the edit modal, you're telling CueDeck:

62
00:03:27,550 --> 00:03:29,550
stop the cascade here.

63
00:03:29,850 --> 00:03:33,600
Watch what happens when I apply a delay with an

64
00:03:33,900 --> 00:03:35,900
anchor session in the list.

65
00:03:36,200 --> 00:03:38,825
The sessions between the live one and

66
00:03:39,125 --> 00:03:41,125
the lunch break all shifted.

67
00:03:41,425 --> 00:03:44,050
But the lunch break itself didn't move.

68
00:03:44,350 --> 00:03:46,350
Neither did anything after it.

69
00:03:46,650 --> 00:03:48,900
The anchor absorbed the delay —

70
00:03:49,200 --> 00:03:52,575
it acts as a firewall for your fixed-time commitments.

71
00:03:52,875 --> 00:03:55,875
And in the delay strip at the top,

72
00:03:56,175 --> 00:03:59,550
you'll see the anchor is called out by name:

73
00:03:59,850 --> 00:04:03,600
it tells you the cascade stopped at 'Lunch Break, 13:00'.

74
00:04:03,900 --> 00:04:07,650
That's your reminder that your afternoon is still on schedule.

75
00:04:07,950 --> 00:04:11,700
There's a second set of controls that's specifically for the

76
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:14,625
session that's currently LIVE: the nudge buttons.

77
00:04:14,925 --> 00:04:17,550
These are different from the delay cascade.

78
00:04:17,850 --> 00:04:21,600
Nudge only affects the session that's running right now —

79
00:04:21,900 --> 00:04:26,400
it moves its end time by one minute without cascading anything downstream.

80
00:04:26,700 --> 00:04:28,700
It's for micro-corrections.

81
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:32,375
If a speaker wraps up a minute early and

82
00:04:32,675 --> 00:04:36,425
you want to give the AV team a slightly longer

83
00:04:36,725 --> 00:04:38,725
transition window, hit minus-one.

84
00:04:39,025 --> 00:04:43,900
If they need just one more minute to finish their thought, hit plus-one.

85
00:04:44,200 --> 00:04:47,200
The timer in the live card updates immediately,

86
00:04:47,500 --> 00:04:52,000
and so does the stage timer display if you have one connected.

87
00:04:52,300 --> 00:04:54,300
Small adjustments, no drama.

88
00:04:54,600 --> 00:04:56,850
Now let's say the session that

89
00:04:57,150 --> 00:05:00,900
was running late actually ended on time after all —

90
00:05:01,200 --> 00:05:04,200
or maybe you applied a delay by accident,

91
00:05:04,500 --> 00:05:07,125
or the event got back on track.

92
00:05:07,425 --> 00:05:10,425
You want to wipe the slate clean and

93
00:05:10,725 --> 00:05:12,975
go back to the original programme.

94
00:05:13,275 --> 00:05:15,900
Hit Reset delays in the orange strip.

95
00:05:16,200 --> 00:05:19,200
CueDeck asks for a single confirmation tap —

96
00:05:19,500 --> 00:05:21,750
it changed to 'Confirm reset?' —

97
00:05:22,050 --> 00:05:24,050
because this is destructive.

98
00:05:24,350 --> 00:05:29,225
Once I confirm, every session's scheduled times go back to their planned originals.

99
00:05:29,525 --> 00:05:31,525
Every delay tag disappears.

100
00:05:31,825 --> 00:05:33,825
The delay strip goes away.

101
00:05:34,125 --> 00:05:36,125
The programme is clean again.

102
00:05:36,425 --> 00:05:39,425
Under the hood, CueDeck is writing `scheduled_start` and

103
00:05:39,725 --> 00:05:43,475
`scheduled_end` back to `planned_start` and `planned_end` for every affected session,

104
00:05:43,775 --> 00:05:46,025
and zeroing out both delay counters.

105
00:05:46,325 --> 00:05:48,575
A few things worth knowing when

106
00:05:48,875 --> 00:05:50,875
you're running a multi-room event.

107
00:05:51,175 --> 00:05:54,925
First: the cascade only touches sessions in the same programme

108
00:05:55,225 --> 00:05:57,475
sequence as the session you delayed.

109
00:05:57,775 --> 00:06:01,150
It works through sort order, not through room assignment.

110
00:06:01,450 --> 00:06:04,450
So if Hall A is running late and

111
00:06:04,750 --> 00:06:09,250
you delay Hall A's keynote, sessions in Hall B are not touched.

112
00:06:09,550 --> 00:06:13,300
You'd apply a delay to Hall B separately if needed.

113
00:06:13,600 --> 00:06:16,225
Second: the cascade stops at ENDED and

114
00:06:16,525 --> 00:06:19,150
CANCELLED sessions too — it skips them.

115
00:06:19,450 --> 00:06:23,200
So if a session was cancelled earlier in the day,

116
00:06:23,500 --> 00:06:26,125
it won't interfere with the propagation logic.

117
00:06:26,425 --> 00:06:29,800
Third: for events with a hard parallel track —

118
00:06:30,100 --> 00:06:33,850
say, a workshop that always runs from two to three

119
00:06:34,150 --> 00:06:36,400
regardless of the plenary room —

120
00:06:36,700 --> 00:06:40,075
make the first session of that track an anchor.

121
00:06:40,375 --> 00:06:44,125
That way no director action on the main stage can

122
00:06:44,425 --> 00:06:46,675
accidentally push your workshop slots around.

123
00:06:46,975 --> 00:06:50,725
And finally: the delay strip is visible to all roles

124
00:06:51,025 --> 00:06:55,150
in director view, not just the person who applied the delay.

125
00:06:55,450 --> 00:06:59,200
So your whole team can see at a glance that

126
00:06:59,500 --> 00:07:02,500
the programme is running plus-ten and plan accordingly.

127
00:07:02,800 --> 00:07:06,175
The delay cascade is one of those features that

128
00:07:06,475 --> 00:07:09,100
sounds complicated until you've used it once,

129
00:07:09,400 --> 00:07:14,275
and then you wonder how you ever ran a live event without it.

130
00:07:14,575 --> 00:07:16,825
One click shifts your entire programme.

131
00:07:17,125 --> 00:07:19,375
Anchor sessions protect your fixed times.

132
00:07:19,675 --> 00:07:23,425
Nudge gives you per-minute surgical control on the running session.

133
00:07:23,725 --> 00:07:27,475
And reset brings everything back to plan in two taps.

134
00:07:27,775 --> 00:07:31,525
In the next episode we're moving into the digital signage

135
00:07:31,825 --> 00:07:35,575
system — how to set up displays around your venue

136
00:07:35,875 --> 00:07:39,250
and get them all pulling live data from CueDeck.

137
00:07:39,550 --> 00:07:41,550
See you there.
